I love coffee, and a particular fantasy of mine would be to go to all these exotic places, make friends with the natives, tour their coffee plantations, sample their wares, and pack my bags with a supply of their goods. (Of course, I would pay them dearly for their goods and services.)

Since I can't go to any of these places, I have to settle for imported coffee. This box of coffee is "Organic Medium Ethiopia Yirgacheffe", "ethically farmed-artisan roasted", and is also fair trade certified and USDA approved.

This particular coffee that I am reviewing is "exotic floral and berry". This particular box has 15 individual, individually-wrapped (that's the part I like!) servings.

I made this coffee this morning, and I love it. It isn't very strong, so it might not be for everyone. (Sometimes coffee is just too strong.) I plan on making more of this coffee later today.

I currently don't have an Espresso machine in my kitchen, but I hope to one day have one. Whenever that time comes, I look forward to the day that I can make cappuccinos and other exotic coffee drinks with all these exotic coffees.

UDDATE Sunday, April 15, 2012: I did make more coffee last night (the coffee was so good - who could resist?); however, that was a big mistake. I did not go to bed until early this morning; consequently, I slept late, missed church, and the day was ruined. (I will go to church tonight.) The caffiene must have been strong. From now on, I will only drink this coffee in the morning. I sure wish I had of had this coffee back when I was in the Army and had to pull all-night duty.

Summary: Easy to use but not as good as the real thing
Text: I love a good mojito but since they are very labor intensive I very seldom make them myself.  Making simple syrup, cutting up limes, and muddling mint with sugar are a long process for me and most of the time not really worth it since I just end up drinking one or two and then have to clean up the mess.  Prior to trying Crystal Light's Moctails I had been making a low sugar alternative to the margarita using Crystal Light lemonade and really enjoyed it so these pre-mixed packets seemed like a good solution.  All you need to do to make these is stir the packet with water which is even possible for someone that is lazy like me.  I added ice and clear rum and voila! instant mojito party time.  Unfortunately these didn't quite live up to the original, they have an odd after-taste that is mildly off putting which I usually attribute to artificial sweeteners.  Most of my guests agreed that these were an okay alternative but just plain they don't seem like a great substitute.  I used this mix and muddled up some mint with them and added a squirt of lime and that seemed to make it much better, but at that point I might as well just make real mojitos rather than using the mix.  Overall I would say if you're a real mojito aficionado you can skip these; if you're a novice and just want to get an idea of the flavors without a lot of work then these would be a good way to get your feet wet.

My canine companion is a 132 pound, five year old, Shiloh Shepherd. The Shiloh Shepherd is considered a 'giant breed.' With his enormous size, athleticism, and the general nutrient demands, we all must consider, his diet has always been a primary consideration. Not to mention, he has the sensitive tummy often seen among the German Shepherd breed. His breeder has always been partial to 'Premium Edge Lamb.' This is the formula he was weaned on. I had no desire to change what appeared to be a successful regimen.

Then to my dismay, I learned 'Premium Edge' was placed on a recent recall list. I knew that a change in diet was likely to be detrimental to my fur friend, but I had to take immediate action. And, at the time of recall, I didn't have time to gradually transition to a new diet, which is always the way to go, to avoid negative symptoms.

After carefully analyzing formulas of numerous dry kibble, I opted to give Pinnacle (Trout & Sweet Potato) a try, ordering a 15 pound 'starter' bag from Amazon. In addition, I ordered some digestive enzymes to assist in the transition phase.

The bag arrived. I opened it with my dog assisting to see what his response would be. The first whiff out of the bag was strong, smelling of fish. I noted the kibble size, itself, was quite small for a large breed dog, but felt this was only a minor reservation. The ultimate test was not what I thought about it, but what my Shiloh would. He immediately had a positive response. In fact --- he loves it! He appears more enthusiastic about it than the 'Premium Edge.'

I had to start the Pinnacle before the enzymes arrived, so I was expecting some terrible gas and possibly some diarrhea. Well, that was not the case. He has gone through the 15 pound bag, and half of the next order --- a 30 pound bag, with no diarrhea, or gas, at all. In fact, his stools appear firmer and more consistent than on his previous diet. Supplementing with the enzymes was actually not necessary.

I'm delighted with this new regimen. I also love that I can order a 30 pound bag through Amazon and have it delivered to my front door. I'm now avoiding a considerable drive, and, the back-breaking-discomfort, of lugging around heavy bags of kibble.

My dog is happy, and I'm happy. That said, after an adequate therapeutic trial, I feel confident in recommending Pinnacle.

Maranatha "All Natural" No Stir, Crunchy, Almond Butter

This is a delicious product, with just enough crunch.

Ingredients: Dry Roasted Almonds, Organic Unrefined Cane Sugar, Palm Oil, Sea Salt.

Some comments:

I believe "All Natural" is what Maranatha calls their slightly cheaper nut-butters whose ingredients don't all meet the Organic standard (if you care strongly about that).

From the label: "... Our unique process also means that you can spread our almond butter right after opening--no need to stir. ..."

Actually, I believe the palm oil is just as important as the "unique process" in keeping the product homogeneous. The palm oil gives this version of Maranatha Almond Butter a creamy texture similar to regular peanut butters with partially hydrogenated vegetable oil. This "no stir" version may be a good choice for people who aren't willing to deal with nut-butters having an inch of separated nut oil on top. I took off a star in part because I don't believe people are expecting palm oil, which is very rich and not in the standard home kitchen, in a Maranatha product.

That said, I bought a single jar in a retail shop. It did benefit from knife-stirring, as a bit of oil was visible on top ("use by" date was 7 months away). No big deal.

You have to love almond butter. I ate a jar in a week, and went back for more. I attribute this product's deliciousness to the added sugar & salt, roasted (not raw) almonds (it smells so good!), and the added palm oil. And the just-right crunchiness, of course.

I admit I have been addicted to hazelnut coffee for years, especially for the first pot in the morning. Even when I find something I like I can't help but experiment. I think I am like many coffee lovers, always looking for that perfect blend, no matter how much we may like what we already have. I drank Harmony hazelnut for years. It is a staple item at one of those warehouse markets here where I do my regular shopping. There is no question that Harmony is a bargain for flavored coffee. I think you would be hard pressed to find a better deal on a hazelnut blend anywhere, even here on Amazon. And there is also no doubt that it is a decent coffee, I drank it for years as already stated. However as also before mentioned, when it comes to the perfect cup of coffee, I just can't help but wonder if the grass over the next rise is really greener. I one day picked up another Hazelnut and realized then that though the Harmony is a decent blend and great bargain, there is no doubt in mind that is it most definitely a weaker blend. Even compared to other regular supermarket brands. And I found it very "hollow" tasting in comparison to other fancier hazelnuts on Amazon that do not cost that much more, (like Melitta's Hazelnut Creme, much stronger). I have since parted ways with Harmony and gone for the stronger brew in a variety of blends that cost a little bit more. In conclusion, I recommend Harmony if you are a hazelnut junkie and have limited funds to support the habit. However if you are someone that like me is on a never ending quest for the cup of java to die for, I suggest you skip this bargain and keep looking. You may not settle on what I have, but it's my feeling you will come to the same conclusion that the Harmony is a good deal, but a weak competitor at best...

PS: A recent review of this blend has shown that it is no longer the great bargain it used to be. Not only is Harmony not eligible for free shipping, but it is also not available for the subscription service where one gets a discount, and free shipping. I have since lowered the rating of this coffee to 3 stars. No longer the bargain it once was, but still just as weak...

Summary: Kibble size - 8 lb. vs. 16 lb. bag
Text:
UPDATE: No word on the kibble size, however the 16 lb. size lasted about 6 - 7 weeks for my Westie. Then the remaining 1/4 bag turned moldy. If you have a small dog, stay with the 8 lb. bag!

My 11 yr. old Westie loves this food. His breed suffers from skin issues. We see improvement with his skin, he's more lively - and he's definitely more enthusiastic about eating!

I bought the 8 lb. bag to try it. This time I bought the 16 lb. bag. There's a big difference in the kibble size with the 16 lb. being not quite double - but significantly bigger. Westies are not big dogs. He's doing okay with it. I've contacted Laughing Dog to see if that's normal. I didn't see a difference in the product description or on the bag - unless I'm missing something.

Anyway - great product! I feel better knowing he's getting good natural ingredients and extra nutrition.

This tea tastes almost as good as the tea you would get at an Indian restaurant. It's much better than getting a teabag and making it the English way, with a lot of water and a bit of milk. This is very creamy and tasty. My only criticism is that there aren't enough sachets in the box. Only 10. Since the directions say that you use one sachet for 100ml of water (approximately half a cup), it's not enough for a good cup of tea, so I use two. That means that one box is only good enough for five cups of tea. But it's a delicious after-dinner drink! I would buy this again if there were more sachets in a box.

Summary: Acquired taste, but oh so addictive.
Text: I decided to try these after reading a blurb about them in our newspaper.  It's hard to compare them to pretzels, other than the shape.  I'm so-so about pretzels (I find them boring), but these are anything but boring.  The crunch is absolutely addictive.  Even my husband, who is less than forgiving about "healthy food that tastes too healthy", loves them.  We bought a second bag at the grocery store (4.49 per bag) before deciding that buying them by the case (at 3.46 per bag) was definitely the way to go.  My only hesitation in doing so was wondering how far out the expiration dates would go.  I'm hoping that the expiration date on the shipment of 12 is at least 2 to 3 months in the future.  Don't let me down, Amazon!

The best thing about these cookies is that they do work. The first time I used them, I lost 13 lbs in 5 weeks! With no exercise. And that was without following the suggested plan exactly. Instead of eating all 6 cookies + dinner and nothing else, I ate 4 cookies during the day, a sensible dinner (probably around 500 calories, but I wasn't really counting), and had a cereal snack bar with hot chocolate made from skim milk for my evening snack.

I stopped with the diet cookies at Thanksgiving 2009, and ate the holiday junk all through December and January. Now (March), I am back on the cookies. I had gained back 8 of the 13 lbs I had lost, but have now lost 2 lbs in 3 days on the cookies. This time around, I am exercising too, but very carefully, since my caloric intake is so low.

When I started with the cookies, I was very nervous about the taste. I am VERY picky about how things taste, and diet cookies just didn't sound very appealing. They really aren't bad. I mean, don't get me wrong, these aren't Oreos. If they were, I'd eat the whole bag in one meal, which would completely defeat the purpose! But they are edible. I have only been eating the blueberry and the chocolate ones (I don't like bananas or coconut, so I figured a diet cookie with those flavors would be even worse), and they actually taste like blueberries and chocolate. There are actually blueberries in the blueberry ones. The chocolate ones smell kind of funny, a lot like protein. But they taste much better than they smell. In fact, my 3 year-old daughter is always asking to "share Mommy special cookies" because she likes them so much (she gets a little bite off of one every so often).

The cookies are kind of small, but are surprisingly filling. I can eat one cookie every 2 hours, and not be hungry in between. In fact, I can almost set my clock by my hunger pangs. As soon as I feel hungry again, I eat another cookie. The cookies are very dense, so they also take me about 10 minutes each to eat. They are a tad dry, but that probably lends to the desire to drink more water, which I do. In fact, I usually hate water, but when I eat these cookies, I crave it, so I drink probably 8 times more water eating the cookies as I do when I don't eat them, which is an added health (and diet) benefit.

They are also great in that they help me get over my emotional eating habits. These cookies are not "comfort food"; I eat them so that I'm not hungry. Over time, they cut down on my desire to be emotionally fulfilled by food. It actually took me almost one full month to go back to my emotional eating habits when I stopped eating the cookies the last time. Since these cookies are not intended to be a forever diet, this separation of emotions from food is a very good thing. Now that I am aware of it, I will just need to be more careful once I reach my desired weight goal and go off the cookies to make sure I don't allow my old habits to once again take hold.

They are a bit pricey for my liking, but most diet food is. And they last me a while, since I have 2 cookies left over every day.

Overall, I really like them. They get an immediate result, which motivates me to keep going. I am working on getting sick of them, but that's a problem I have with any food I eat a whole lot of (I miss pb&j sandwiches, but I overloaded in 5th grade). I doubt many other people would have that issue.

I subscribed to this as a replacement for beef stew that Amazon discontinued. The beef stew came with token vegetables, potatoes, lots of gravy and some cubes made of textured beef product. It wasn't too bad when doctored with red wine, spices, extra vegetables, and brown rice.

There are no potatoes, or token vegetables here, and the textured beef cubes have been replaced with actual chunks of beef with the Libby roast beef. The chunks are slightly tough, have a pronounced grain, and actually taste something like beef. Having gone through six cans, I have found very little excess fat or gristle.

It's pretty easy to whip up a quickie beef stew with this stuff. Frozen veggies, rice or potatoes, a can of diced or stewed tomatoes, some spices and wine, and you have a perfectly serviceable, quickie meal.

For those who argue that made from scratch tastes better, you are right. For those who argue that home made is just as easy, well, I have a bridge I can sell you ... ;)

Wow, for a Hummus that is pre-packaged and needs no refrigeration it tastes fantastic, if not better than most Hummus that you can find in the refrigerator section of the supermarket. I bought a "go picnic" box which contained this and was really surprised at how delicious this hummus is. It is the perfect portion size and would be great in a kid's (or adult's) lunchbox with a handful of crackers. You can slip this in your purse or back-pack, it's quite durable the packaging, and eat it when you need something healthy and filling. By the way, check out the Go Picnic ready-to-eat meals. I first found them at Cost Plus World Market, but have since found them on Amazon. Their meal with this same "Wild Garden" Hummus also comes with rice crackers, some chocolate, edamame and a fruit and nut mix, it's fantastic, especially if you don't have the time to put together your own healthy snack or lunch box. I left mine in the car for months and just ate it and it was still really good.

Summary: Tastes like regular pasta, easy and quick too
Text:

I would definately recommend this (and any of) Mrs. Leeper's product.

I do recommend using more water than to-the-line; I fill it to a good centimeter or so (it's kinda imprecise) above the line, and let it sit awhile to absorb.

Summary: tasty, but a tad on the dry side
Text:
I hardly noticed the raisins in this cookie, which is great if you don't like raisins, but I do like them. The oatmeal flavor for the cookie is just as it should be. When first opening the packet the aroma hinted at maybe a pinch of cinnamon added or maybe nutmeg in the mix.

The consistency though was spongy, and rather dry. I needed something to drink with it to help moisten it up.

Should be called potatoes with corned beef.

Flavor of corned beef was missing, maybe because it was reduced fat.

Consider it storage food.
